n't find a concrete advantage with the other two rook moves and this one is more principled. 2 rooks in the center open files. } { [%clk 1:09:00] } (16. Red1 { Other candidate. }) (16. Rac1 { Other candidate. }) 16... Rg6 { [%clk 1:15:00] } 17. Ne8 { I really hate free pawns I guess... } { [%clk 1:06:00] } 17... h6 { This move surprised me but it seemed to not work that well for black. } { [%clk 1:11:00] } (17... Bg4 { I thought this was interesting. } 18. Nxd6+ Rxd6 { Since black could now take back with the rook. }) 18. Nxd6+ { My "attack" kind of failed. I didn't find anything winning and this seemed like a way to win back the pawn. While leaving black with a very uncoordinated position. } { [%clk 1:06:00] } 18... cxd6 { [%clk 1:12:00] } 19. Bxd8 { Wanted to remove the bishop from the attack of the pawn and I liked that I would then be taking the pawn back with check. } { [%clk 1:05:00] } 19... Kxd8 { [%clk 1:12:00] } 20. Ne5 { This looked better than Rxd6 right away. It forces black to move the rook and allows me to have a more active knight after I take on d6 which turned out to be very true as that knight was a beauty in the endgame. } { [%clk 1:00:00] } (20. Rxd6+ { This was my original plan but then I stopped for a bit to see if I could find something better. }) 20... Rg8 { [%clk 1:10:00] } 21. Rxd6+ { [%clk 1:00:00] } 21... Kc7 { [%clk 1:10:00] } 22. Red1 { Maybe should have retreated instead but I was hoping she would maybe blunder something. } { [%clk 1:00:00] } 22... Rad8 { That said this is the move she went for and I saw no way to avoid the trade of rooks. } { [%clk 1:07:00] } (22... a6 { For example... } 23. Nxf7 Bxf7 24. Rd7+ Kb6 25. Rxf7 { I could win a pawn like this if black did nothing. }) 23. Rxd8 { [%clk 0:58:00] } (23. Nxc4 { I considered this. } 23... Bxc4 (23... Rxd6 24. Rxd6 { Here I lose everything } (24. Nxd6 Rd8 { And here I lose everything too })) 24. Rxd8 Rxd8 25. Rc1 { But here my rook is pinned to the back rank. }) 23... Rxd8 { Last 